metadata.name: AlgoRhythm #79
metadata.description:
[Controls]
<Keyboard>
Adjust animation speed: UP/DOWN ARROWS
Pause/Resume animation: SPACEBAR
Toggle texture: T
HD size: H
Save as PNG: S

<Touchscreen>
Toggle animation speed: Tap on the artwork
Save as PNG: Tap on the completed artwork

<Url parameters>
Set image pixels: px={number}. eg: px=1000
Set slow rendering speed from the beginning: s=1

[Algorithm]
The project is named after the prototype of my various projects, inspired by The Delaunays' Rhythm series of paintings. The prototype generates connected concentric circle groups with a composition checker, to ensure that each output has a sufficiently balanced composition. In this project, I showcased its ability to adapt to arbitrary aspect ratios.

Each stroke is drawn by a library that builds on my previous project, Rose 1851. Every stroke could be rendered in an animated manner, in that case, the entire rendering process is as if we are witnessing how an artist creates a painting from scratch. In this project, the default setting is the fastest rendering speed, but you can also adjust the speed manually to watch how the work is drawn stroke by stroke.

[Palettes]
There are a total of 35 palettes in this project, including 27 made from my photography, others drawn from 8 paintings from the 18th to early 20th centuries.


Note: This work is GPU intensive. The live, the animation might not run on some mobile devices at the default image size. You can add “?px=1000" to the end of your edition's URL and adjust the number to manually set the size of the image.

metadata.name: Cellular Skyscrapers #250
metadata.description:
A "Cellular Skyscraper" originates from a 15x15 grid with 15x3 cells randomly assigned the 'alive' state. According to the cellular automaton rule chosen from the transaction hash 24 new generations are calculated and placed on top of each other.

There are four different rules available (listed in Golly notation) all based on the Moore neighbourhood: 

B3/S23 (Game of Life)
B36/S125 (2x2)
B368/S245 (Morley)
B3/S234 (didn't find a name for it but produces interesting large structures)

After all generations have been calculated the algorithm searches through the complete 3D grid to find the one structure consisting of the most connected alive cells - cells are connected when they have at least one alive neighbour in any of the three axis.

Features are cell count, height, highlight color, ca rule and antenna count.

Extra: press 'd' to download the structure as a .gltf file to import into Blender or other software.
 
Enjoy!

metadata.name: Tessellatum #19
metadata.description:
Tessellatum – a collection inspired by mosaic and weaving craftworks.

The artworks were created by applying a p5.js generative algorithm simulating mosaic, pointillism and weaving-like textures on a library of images issued/exported from a generative flowfield algorithm in R (The R Project for Statistical Computing). In other words, to avoid any ambiguity, the R issued images on which the mosaics effects are applied are not generated on the fxhash platform, but the mosaic effects (noise, size and shape of the tiles), the backgrounds and various other generative elements are via a p5.js implementation.

metadata.name: Wandering Nets #61
metadata.description:
Wandering Nets is a digital kinetic light sculpture by Matt Ebb.

Networks of light are created and connected via random walks in space and colour. Emergent structures are revealed by the ambient interaction, tension and collision of these networks within themselves and orbiting shadowed spherical bodies.

The piece is the result of several months of custom development in realtime volume rendering. The scene data is generated in javascript and rendered with a bespoke GLSL raytracer - no external libraries are used.

This is a graphically intensive shader. By default it will adaptively adjust sampling quality to target 30fps, though a reasonably fast GPU is recommended for best results. 

Mouse drag: Orbit the camera in 3D to explore compositions
[ and ] keys: Override the adaptive samples per pixel lower or higher to trade noise for framerate

March 2022

metadata.name: Sketchbook Splash #149
metadata.description:
A splash of color on some scribbled shapes.

There are several keybindings to modify the image:
'1' - Toggles watercolors
'2' - Toggles overlaying constrast shapes 
'3' - Toggles sketch outlines
'4' - Toggles shape/splatter clipping (will fill the entire canvas with watercolor!)
'B' - Cycles borders; black, white, all colors in the palette being used, and no border

Play around to find something you like, and then press 'S' to download a copy of your image. 
You can also modify the URL parameters at the end of the URL to change the size of the image, such as &x=2560&y=1440. Keep in mind that this will result in a slightly different image, but colors/shapes/general layout will remain the same. The default size is 2048x2048.

@teaboswell, 2022

metadata.name: Whisper #104
metadata.description:
Abstract forms built with noise and texture

-------------

A note on rendering times: *Whisper has a lot going on*. It can take up to 1-5 minutes to fully render, depending on your hardware configuration, including a 15sec-1min loading phase during which lots of calculations take place (but no visuals). It'll get there, just be patient! A small loading bar along the bottom also shows the progression of the render during the drawing phase.

Press 'S' or click "Save image" to save a PNG version of the artwork while in full-screen/IPFS view

Customisation
-------------

The following parameters can be adjusted in full-screen mode.
Open the token in full-screen/IPFS mode, and add any of these to the URL:

&size=2000 (replace 2000 with any value up to around 8000) - this sets the resolution/width of the canvas in pixels. Use this to generate very large PNG images (50MB+) suitable for printing at large DPI & canvas sizes. The max value here is dependent on your hardware, might not work on mobiles etc.

&ratio=1.4 (any value between 1 and 2, default = 1.4) - set the aspect ratio of the work. By default Whisper renders at 1:1.4 but you can change this to match other printing formats. Different ratios will produce slightly different outputs, but the overall character of the artwork should still be present. Landscape mode is not supported.

metadata.name: Sprocket Factory #415
metadata.description:
Just an ordinary scene from a typical day, working as a Sprocket Factory engineer. Inspiration for this work is drawn from the composable nature of blockchain smart contracts and the flow of value between networks of autonomous machines and free-willed individuals.

"A Doodle, Ringer, and Fidenza walk into a Space Bar..."

- Live renderer best viewed in Chrome.
- Press "P" to export an PNG raster image (10k resolution.)
- Press "S" to export an SVG vector.

metadata.name: Pandora #45
metadata.description:
Pandora received many gifts from the Gods: beauty, flattery, kindness, skill, grace, intelligence, but also the art of deception and seduction. They gave her the name Pandora (Πανδώρα), “endowed with all the gifts” in Greek.

The Pandora generative series has the same qualities as the mythological figure. Able to adopt many different shapes, a wide variety of colors and styles, all created from simple rules.

Only one thing though, do not open the box.

[S] key to save a PNG image
Press once for a resolution of 2000x2000, a second time for a resolution of 4000x4000, then 6000x6000 and finally 8000x8000

Made with p5.js

Artist: Estienne
April 2022
License: NFT 2.0
